E-mail: javier.gomez@invemar.org.co  Phone: +575 4328600 ext 231  Aims:  To  isolate  microorganisms  associated  to  marine  –  coastal  sediments  of  colombian  Caribbean  and  for  evaluating  its  antimicrobial  activity  in  order  to  identify  the  most  active  Methods  and  Results:  104  strains  were  isolated  from  sediment  samples  of  the  colombian  Caribbean. First at all, an antimicrobial activity screening was made using agar well diffusion  method  against  the  pathogens:  Escherichia  coli,  Staphylococcus  aureus,  Klebsiella  pneumoniae, Candida albicans, Candida tropicalis and Pseudomonas aeruginosa. 17 strains  showed  strong  antimicrobial  activity  and  were  identified  as  members  of  the  Streptomyces,

Micrococcus  and  Bacillus  genera.  Organic  extracts  were  produced  by  liquid  –liquid  extraction  and  HPLC  profiles  of  the  most  active  extracts  were  obtained.  Then,  the  antimicrobial activity of the extracts was evaluated with the broth microdilution test, finding  antimicrobial  activities  superior  to  90%  against  S.  aureus  MRSA    and  C.  albicans.  HPLC  profiles indicated the presence of different antimicrobial compounds.  Conclusion: This study indicates the presence of marine microorganisms from the colombian  Caribbean that produce compounds with antimicrobial activity against pathogenic strains.  Significance  and  Impact  of  Study:  These  results,  contribute  to  the  knowledge  of  the  biotechnological  potential  of  pharmaceutical products that can counteract the increasing problem of pathogens resistance. Additionally, it has been report that the ocean floor  is  the  font  of  unique  forms  of  bacteria  with  special  adaptation  characteristics  (e.g.  lack  of  light,  high  acidity,  high  pressure,  low  temperature  and  variable  oxygen  concentration  and  salinity), which induce the production of secondary metabolites with complex structures and  bioactivity (Kodzius and Gojobori, 2015).

From  them,  antibiotics  constitute  a  significant  group  produced  particularly  by  marine-derived  bacteria  of  Pseudoalteromonas  spp.,  Vibrionaceae,  Firmicutes,  Roseobacter  clade,  Pseudomonas  spp.,  and Cyanobacteria. Some of the most common compounds discovered from marine bacteria  include  marinopyrroles,  bisanthraquinones,  salinisporamycin,  arenimycin,  abyssomicin,  pentabromopseudilin,  indolmycin,  violacein,  korormycin,  tetrabromopyrrole,  thiomarinols,  bogorol  A,  macrolactin  T,  ieodoglucomides  A  and  B,  tauramamide,  tropodithietic  acid  (TDA),  2,4  –  diacetylphloroglucinol  (DAPG),  malyngolide,  hormothamnin  A,  and  ariakemicins A and B (Wietz et al., 2013). But  until  now  the  studies about  marine  bacteria in  Colombia  have been concentrated  in the  search  of  bacteria  for crude oil biodegradation (Díaz et al., 2011; Revelo et al., 2013), bacteria associated with  the snail blade (Acosta et al., 2009; Moreno et al., 2010), and bacteria for the degradation of  organic  contaminants  (Sánchez  and  Henry,  2012).  Taking  in  account  how  little  is  known

about  microbial  biodiversity,  and  the  few  antimicrobial  studies  that  have  been  made  with  marine  microorganisms  for  pharmaceutical  interests,  the  aim  of  the  present  work  was  to  isolate  native  microorganisms  associated  with  marine-coastal  environments,  and  evaluate  their antimicrobial activity identifying the most active strains.  Sample collection and bacteria isolation   Collection of sediment samples was made in two sectors of the colombian Caribbean Sea at  the Magdalena department known as “Caño Aguas Negras” (CAN: 10° 48' 41.8"N; 074° 36'  24.95"W)  and  “Punta  Betin”  (PBE:  11°15'  01.94"N;  074°  13'  10.73"W)  characterized  by  different  charge  of  organic  material  (figure  1  and  table  S1).  Studies  made  by  INVEMAR  (2017)  in  sampling  sites  near  to  CAN  reported  values  of  Biochemical  Oxygen  Demand  (BDO5)  in  a  range  of  6.35  mg  l-1  and  69.2  mg  l-1  in  2016.  Nonetheless,  sampling  sites  in  Santa Marta near to PBE reported BDO5 values of 3.35 mg  l-1 and 0.72 mg l-1. These values  indicate  that  CAN  presents  high  content  of  biodegradable  organic  matter  in  comparison  to  PBE. Sample collection was made using a Van Veen dredge in a surface of 0.08 m2, during  the sample collection the salinity of the sampling point CAN was 3.8 and PBE was 36.4. For  bacteria isolation, 20 grams of sediments were subjected to heat treatment (50 °C, 60 min) to  eliminate  vegetative  microbiota  (Rocha et al.,  2013). A high  quantity  of  isolates  were  obtained  with  the  culture  media  TSA  –  I  and  MA,  most  of  the  colonies formed were slightly humid and somewhat shiny, circular and irregular forms were  predominant  although  some  isolates  were  rhizoids.  Colonies  color  varys  from  white  to  orange. Microscopically, cocci and bacillus Gram positive (some with spores and filamentous  cells)  were  observed.  Similar  results  were  found  in  previous  studies  (Duncan  et  al.,  2014;  Graça  et  al.,  2015;  León  et  al.,  2011).  On  the  other  hand,  in  these  ecosystems,  two  competition  types  could  affect  the  rates  of  microbial  growth:  an  interspecies  competition  where the abundant bacteria have a great ability to compete for the resources in comparison  to  the  rare  bacteria  and  an  intra–species  competition  where  the  resources  are  limited  decreasing  microbial  growth  rates.  This  competition  explains  the  presence  of  inactive  and  bacteria with high metabolic rate in the same aquatic environment (Campbell et al., 2011).

This is a good result considering that MRSA is an increasing global problem, and it only can  This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.  The counting of cultivable bacteria was higher in CAN than in PBE, probably because  Although the majority of the cultivable bacteria were from CAN, the most active strains  be affected by vancomycin and teicoplanin (Lee et al., 2013). On the other hand, no highest  antimicrobial  activity  against  E  coli  ESBL  was  evident.  This  was  probably  because  its  pathogenic  nature  related  to  the  production  of extended  spectrum  beta-lactamases  confers a  resistant  mechanism  against  multiple  antibiotics,  turning  it  into  a  difficult  blank  to  attack.  Similar results were obtained by Duncan et al. (2014), where the more susceptible strains to  be inhibited were MRSA and C. albicans. Also, (Graça et al., 2015) reported that the 83% of  the  isolated  strains  were  active  against  C.  albicans  and  only  4%  against  E.  coli.  Consequently, the microorganisms evaluated could be broad spectrum metabolite producers.  especially  those  that  are  part  of  the  Bacillus,  Micrococcus,  Pseudomonas,  Vibrio,  Flavobacterium, Alteromonas (Sinimol et al., 2016) and Streptomyces genera (Dalisay et al.,  2013; Rashad et al., 2015). In this study, Bacillus was the prominent genus, probably because  the heat treatment killed many non-spore-forming species. This is also in concordance with  previous phylogenetic studies in marine sediments which demonstrated the presence of Gram

positive bacteria specially from the Bacillus genus (Gontang et al., 2007). There are several  reports  about  the  antimicrobial  activity  of  Bacillus  genus,  (Song  et  al.,  2013)  found  that  Bacillus  amyloliquefaciens  isolated  from  mangroves  present  a  high  antimicrobial  activity  against a clinic isolated of C. albicans and (Tabbene et al., 2011) obtained lipopeptides from  Bacillus  subtilis  B38  with  the  same  antifungal  activity.  Furthermore,  (Das  et  al.,  2008)  obtained  a  biosurfactant  from  Bacillus  circulans  active  against  MRSA.  Unfortunately,  although the ribosomal 16S gene used is good for bacteria identification, it does not allow a  good  discrimination  at  species  level  in  some  genera  like  Bacillus,  making  the  use  of  other  molecular  markers  necessary.  An  example  is  the  identification  of  B.  thuringiensis  in  which  the amplification of genes that are codified for the proteins involved in the capsule synthesis  is crucial for the identification at specie level (Jensen, 2016). The 17 active strains were members of  the genera Streptomyces, Micrococcus and Bacillus, the last was the predominant genus. The  antimicrobial activity found can be stimulated by the medium composition and the bacterium  – bacterium interaction. In general, the results observed with the qualitative method of well  diffusion  assay  were  corroborated  with  the  quantitative  antimicrobial  assay  performed  with  the  different  extracts,  finding  growth  inhibition  percentages  greater  than  90%  over  MRSA  and C. albicans. This suggests that the bioactive molecules are of organic nature and can be  separated by HPLC techniques using a modified standard method. These results contribute to  the knowledge of the biotechnological potential of colombian biodiversity for development of  pharmaceutical products that can counteract the increasing problem of pathogens resistance.
